  <p>This article focuses on how Bihar students can think about course selection in a more useful way. The answer is not the same for every student, but the decision framework can be improved significantly.</p>
  <h2>Do not search for the best course in isolation</h2>
  <p>The best course for one student may be the wrong course for another. That is why the best starting point is the <a href="/courses">courses page</a>, where students can compare categories, durations, and general study pathways rather than chasing trends alone.</p>
  <h2>Think in terms of category first</h2>
  <p>Students should ask whether they are more aligned with technical courses, management, healthcare, arts, commerce, education, or flexible distance-learning options. Category-level clarity makes the later university choice much easier.</p>
